commit 71eccb5a4209bb1d3efbe6d19c3bb880c8b70696
Author: Jan Kara <jack@suse.cz>
udf: Fix race between file type conversion and writeback

This commit open-codes the writeback preparation logic in udf_writepages
to serialize file type conversion for in-ICB files by rechecking the
inode type under the folio lock.

Link: https://lore.kernel.org/all/f622c01.67ac.19cdbdd777d.Coremail.luckd0g@163.com

> diff --git a/fs/udf/inode.c b/fs/udf/inode.c
> --- a/fs/udf/inode.c
> +++ b/fs/udf/inode.c
> @@ -181,34 +181,38 @@ static void udf_write_failed(struct address_space *mapping, loff_t to)
[ ... ]
> -static int udf_adinicb_writepages(struct address_space *mapping,
> -		      struct writeback_control *wbc)
> +static int udf_writepages(struct address_space *mapping,
> +			  struct writeback_control *wbc)
>  {
>  	struct inode *inode = mapping->host;
>  	struct udf_inode_info *iinfo = UDF_I(inode);
[ ... ]
> +	if (iinfo->i_alloc_type == ICBTAG_FLAG_AD_IN_ICB) {
> +		struct folio *folio;
> +
> +		folio = filemap_lock_folio(mapping, 0);
> +		if (!folio)
> +			return 0;

Should this check use IS_ERR(folio)? filemap_lock_folio() returns an error
pointer such as ERR_PTR(-ENOENT) on failure, not NULL. If the folio is
absent, checking for NULL evaluates to false, which would pass the error
pointer to folio_prepare_writeback() or folio_unlock() and potentially cause
a panic.

> +		/*
> +		 * Recheck inode type under folio lock when we are protected
> +		 * against udf_expand_file_adinicb(). Bail to standard writeback
> +		 * path if file got expanded.
> +		 */
> +		if (iinfo->i_alloc_type != ICBTAG_FLAG_AD_IN_ICB) {
> +			folio_unlock(folio);

Since filemap_lock_folio() looks up the folio and acquires an elevated
reference count, does this exit path need a corresponding folio_put(folio)
to prevent pinning the folio in memory and causing a leak?

> +			goto mpage_writeback;
> +		}
> +		if (folio_prepare_writeback(mapping, wbc, folio)) {

Does this abort the writeback when it actually succeeds?

folio_prepare_writeback() returns true on success when the folio was dirty
and is ready to be written. As written, this check seems to return 0 and skip
the data copy on success, while proceeding to copy the data if the folio is
clean. Should this check be negated?

> +			folio_unlock(folio);

Is a folio_put() needed on this exit path as well?

> +			return 0;
> +		}
>  		memcpy_from_file_folio(iinfo->i_data + iinfo->i_lenEAttr, folio,
>  				0, i_size_read(inode));
>  		folio_unlock(folio);

Does this path also require a folio_put(folio) after unlocking to release
the reference acquired by filemap_lock_folio()?

> +		mark_inode_dirty(inode);
> +		return 0;
>  	}
[ ... ]

